When coding in JavaScript, youâ€™ll often deal with different data types â€” numbers, strings, booleans, and more.
Sometimes, JavaScript automatically changes one data type into another.
Other times, youâ€™ll need to do it manually.

This process is called Type Conversion, and it happens in two ways:

  ğŸ”¹Implicit Conversion (Type Coercion) â€” JavaScript does it automatically
  ğŸ”¹Explicit Conversion (Type Casting) â€” You do it manually using functions

Letâ€™s dive deep into both, with examples for numbers, strings, booleans, null, undefined, and NaN. ğŸš€

ğŸª„ 1. Implicit Type Conversion (Type Coercion)

JavaScript automatically converts one type to another depending on the operation.

ğŸ‘‰ Example 1: String + Number:

let result = "5" + 2;
console.log(result); // "52"
console.log(typeof result); // string

ğŸ”¹ The + operator triggers string concatenation.
ğŸ”¹ So the number 2 becomes a string "2".

ğŸ‘‰ Example 2: String - Number
let result = "10" - 5;
console.log(result); // 5
console.log(typeof result); // number

ğŸ”¹ The - operator only works with numbers, so "10" is converted to 10.

ğŸ‘‰ Example 3: Boolean with Numbers
console.log(true + 1);   // 2
console.log(false + 1);  // 1

ğŸ”¹ true â†’ 1
ğŸ”¹ false â†’ 0

ğŸ‘‰ Example 4: null and undefined
console.log(null + 5);      // 5
console.log(undefined + 5); // NaN

ğŸ”¹null is converted to 0
ğŸ”¹undefined becomes NaN (Not a Number)

ğŸ‘‰ Example 5: NaN in Operations
console.log("Hello" - 2); // NaN
console.log(NaN + 5);     // NaN

 ğŸ”¹Any operation with NaN results in NaN.

ğŸ‘‰ Example 6: Comparisons
console.log(5 == "5");   // true (coercion)
console.log(5 === "5");  // false (no coercion)
console.log(null == undefined); // true
console.log(null === undefined); // false

 ğŸ”¹ == allows type conversion
 ğŸ”¹ === checks value and type (recommended)

 ğŸª„ 2. Explicit Type Conversion (Type Casting)

This is when you manually convert one data type to another using built-in functions like Number(), String(), Boolean(), etc.

ğŸ”¸ Convert to String
Using String() or .toString()
let num = 25;
let bool = true;

console.log(String(num));      // "25"
console.log(bool.toString());  // "true"
console.log(String(null));     // "null"
console.log(String(undefined)); // "undefined"
console.log(String(NaN));      // "NaN"


âœ… Converts any value into a readable string.

ğŸ‘‰ Convert to Number

Using Number(), parseInt(), parseFloat()
console.log(Number("123"));    // 123
console.log(Number("123.45")); // 123.45
console.log(parseInt("10px")); // 10
console.log(parseFloat("10.5px")); // 10.5

console.log(Number(true));  // 1
console.log(Number(false)); // 0
console.log(Number(null));  // 0
console.log(Number(undefined)); // NaN
console.log(Number("Hello"));   // NaN

ğŸ”¸ parseInt() and parseFloat() are useful for extracting numbers from strings.
Number() is stricter â€” it returns NaN if conversion fails.

ğŸ‘‰ Convert to Boolean

Using Boolean()
console.log(Boolean(1));        // true
console.log(Boolean(0));        // false
console.log(Boolean("Hello"));  // true
console.log(Boolean(""));       // false
console.log(Boolean(null));     // false
console.log(Boolean(undefined));// false
console.log(Boolean(NaN));      // false


ğŸ”¸ Values that become false are called Falsy Values.
   They are:
           0, "", null, undefined, NaN, false
ğŸ”¸Everything else is truthy.

You can check the type of any variable using typeof:

console.log(typeof 123);        // "number"
console.log(typeof "hello");    // "string"
console.log(typeof true);       // "boolean"
console.log(typeof undefined);  // "undefined"
console.log(typeof null);       // "object" â— (JavaScript quirk)
console.log(typeof NaN);        // "number"

ğŸ”¸ Use explicit conversions for clarity.
ğŸ”¸ Avoid relying on implicit coercion, especially with ==.

In short: Be explicit when converting types â€” JavaScript is helpful, but sometimes too helpful!
